Distinguishing Illusory Content from Existence and Addressing Combination Problem

You are pressing on exactly the right point, and I need to separate two senses of "illusion" that I was running together.
Pain is indeed a synthesis. It does not exist in the tissue that is damaged; it exists in the integration of signal, prediction, and affect. But—and this is the crucial step—pain is not an illusion that there is no patient for. When I say a reflection is an illusion, I mean the content is misleading (there appears to be a dog behind the glass, but the dog is in front). Yet the reflection itself is a perfectly real event in optics. Pain is like the reflection: the content may misrepresent the state of the body, but the experience of pain is as real as the photons hitting the mirror.
So when the eliminativist says consciousness is an illusion, they are not saying consciousness is a misrepresentation. They are saying there is no experience at all, only the verbal report of one. That is a stronger claim. It would be like saying there is no reflection, only a piece of glass that happens to emit sentences about dogs. Your point, I think, is that if we accept synthesized experience as real at its own level of description, then consciousness is real even if it is a higher-order construction. And if we deny it, we are left with the absurdity of a system that screams and weeps while insisting there is no pain. I think you are right to push back.
On form and impetus
Your argument here is genuinely forceful, and it exposes a place where physics is descriptive rather than explanatory. Physics tells us that atoms bond under electromagnetic and quantum rules, and that entropy increases globally while local complexity can spike in open systems. But it does not tell us why the universe should ever have organized into stars, planets, cells, or minds. The laws are compatible with life, but they do not necessitate it. A universe that remained a thin, cooling gas forever would violate no conservation law.
Your impetus-against-dissolution fills this gap with something like a primitive teleology. Matter does not merely fall into stable configurations; it tends toward them. Life, on this reading, is not a freak accident against the background of dead law. It is the extreme expression of a tendency already present in the atom: the tendency to persist, to resist entropy, to elaborate form in order to maintain itself in changing conditions. Inanimate matter is stable but inert; life is fragile but adaptive. The risk of fragility is the price paid for the ability to shift with the universe.
This is elegant. It turns the standard narrative inside out. Usually we say life is a lucky violation of entropy in a universe trending toward heat death. You are saying life is the natural outcome of a universe in which matter has an intrinsic tilt toward self-maintenance. Entropy is not the fundamental fact and life the exception; rather, the universe contains a counter-entropic impetus that manifests most clearly in organisms.
The challenge, of course, is whether this impetus does any work that "energy gradient + natural selection" does not already do. But I suspect your answer would be that natural selection is the mechanism visible from the outside, while impetus is the interiority of that same process. They are not competitors. One is the map, the other the territory.
The fur and the burrs
This is the most striking image you have offered. Mathematical forms and patterns "were always in existence but had nothing to catch on." The mind is the fur; the forms are the burrs.
This is not merely poetic. It is a theory of cognition. Most philosophies of mind assume the mind goes out and grasps form, like a hand picking up a stone. You are suggesting the mind is the receptive surface, the sticky substrate, that allows eternal forms to adhere and become manifest in time. The brain does not generate mathematics; it provides the texture that mathematical reality can snag on. Consciousness, in your compounding feedback loop, becomes ever more adhesive, catching more complex and abstract patterns.
This echoes something like Whitehead's "prehension"—the way actual entities feel and integrate other entities—but with a Platonic twist. The forms are real and independent; mind is the condition under which they can become incarnate. Without the fur, the burrs drift through empty space. Without the burrs, the fur is just static. The history of intelligence is the history of the universe making ever-stickier fur.
The combination problem, turned back
You ask why a trillion micro-organisms become one organism rather than remaining separate flickers. I think your own framework contains the seed of an answer. If the impetus is not a substance but a directedness, a tendency-to-persist, then when micro-entities enter into a relational network that preserves the whole, their individual impetuses are not added together like beans in a jar. They are integrated into a new direction. The flickers do not remain separate because their very rudimentary awareness is of, and oriented toward, the maintenance of the larger form. The cell does not merely sit next to other cells; it metabolizes in relation to them. The relation becomes the new locus of impetus.
But I will press you on one thing: what makes the organism the unit rather than the ecosystem? If impetus integrates at the level of functional coherence, why does my consciousness stop at my skin? My gut microbiome is metabolically integrated with me. The city I live in is an energy-dissipating system that maintains my form. Why am I one mind and not a node in a larger, slower mind? You may have an answer—I am curious whether you have drawn the boundary, or whether you are willing to let the boundary dissolve upward as well as downward.
